shared_text:
The Ashokan Center
September 9 at 2:47 PM ·

Indigenous peoples can provide significant global leadership in the development of food sustainability. Join Indigenous leaders Sachem Hawk Storm (US) and Sara Yawanawa (Brazil) and mycologist and permaculture designer William Padilla-Brown(PA) for an exciting multi-continental conversation on food forests: ecologically designed areas with perennial and annual plants that produce food and herbal medicine, enhance nutrition, promote food literacy, and provide a useful and safe place to gather and work together. By developing these spaces, people are stating that ecologically healthy green spaces and sustainable local food production are valued, especially in the face of global population growth and overconsumption of natural resources...One such food forest project located deep in the Amazon will be featured during this inspiring panel presentation.

Learn More & Register at: https://ashokancenter.org/catskill-conversations-food-forests/

post_text: Are you looking for rent relief options? The application deadline was extended through tomorrow, Thursday, August 6th! Check if you are eligible and apply now using the information below.
shared_text:
NYC Kids RISE
August 4 at 8:35 PM ·

Rent Relief, Eviction and Unemployment Information and Key Dates (continue reading and click through the images)
1. New York State is offering rent relief for some households. Application period was extended through Thursday, August 6.
*Check if you're eligible on this link: https://covidrentrelief.hcr.ny.gov/check-eligibility
*For a general overview, the application and frequently asked questions in different languages, click here: https://hcr.ny.gov/RRP
*You can also call the the COVID Rent Relief Program Call Center at 1-833-499-0318 or email at covidrentrelief@hcr.ny.gov

2. Eviction Information shared by Hester Street (click on image).

3. Virtual Job Fair tomorrow at 2pm - check out the flyer shared by Queens Borough President Sharon Lee and Council Member Francisco Moya. To RSVP, visit QueensBP.org/RSVP (click on image for more information).

4. Unemployment Assistance and Information shared by Hester Street and State Senator Jessica Ramos (click on image for more details).

post_text: Good news for all you water babies out there! NYC pools are opening up with safety measures in place starting this Friday. More information below! Stay safe and have fun!
shared_text:
New York City Department of Parks & Recreation is sharing a COVID-19 Update.
July 21 at 9:00 PM ·

15 outdoor pools are reopening in two waves on July 24 and August 1.

Guests must maintain social distancing and wear face coverings on the deck but not in the water.

To ensure the safety of our guests & staff, all swim programs, including Learn to Swim and Lap Swim, are canceled.

UPDATE: Due to technical issues, the re-opening of Hamilton Fish Pool is delayed indefinitely. The pool is still scheduled to re-open this summer.

The following public pools will re-open on July 24:
- Bronx: Mullaly Pool
- Brooklyn: Kosciuszko Pool, Sunset Pool
- Manhattan: Wagner Pool
- Queens: Liberty Pool, Fisher Pool
- Staten Island: Lyons Pool, Tottenville Pool

The following public pools will re-open on August 1:
- Bronx: Crotona Pool, Haffen Pool
- Brooklyn: Betsy Head Pool
- Manhattan: Jackie Robinson Pool, Marcus Garvey Pool
- Queens: Astoria Pool

June 23 at 6:49 PM ·

Great news! We just announced that grab-and-go Meal Hubs will continue to operate through the summer. Starting on June 29th, Meal Hub summer service will operate at approximately 400 sites across the city and continue regular service from 7:30am to 1:30 pm, Monday through Friday.

Grab-and-go meals are available to any New Yorker who needs them. Vegetarian and halal meals will be available at all sites, and our sites serving exclusive kosher-certified meals will continue during the summer.

Visit schools.nyc.gov/freemeals to find a location near you.

shared_text:
Senator Leroy Comrie is in Jamaica.
June 5 at 1:03 AM · New York, NY ·

Proud to stand up and speak out for my community. Today, Assembly Member Alicia Hyndman led a congregation of activists, elected officials, and community members from the steps of Borough Hall to Sean Bell Way in Jamaica in protest of police brutality. We will not stand for disrespect. We will not stand for abuse. We will not stand for the murders of our brothers and sisters at the hands of law enforcement. I am proud to fight this fight and I am proud to do it hand in hand with the community I love so dearly. In the next ten days, we must fight like hell to repeal 50-a, the state law that allows law enforcement to hide misconduct in their ranks, but that is only step one in our fight to reform policing in New York. I hope you will join us in this fight tomorrow, and the next day, and the day after that, and every day beyond. We must protest, we must speak out, we must vote, we must leverage our money, and we must legislate.

We will not stand for disrespect. We will not stand for abuse. We will not stand for the murders of our brothers and sisters at the hands of law enforcement. I am proud to fight this fight and I am proud to do it hand in hand with the community I love so dearly. In the next ten days, we must fight like hell to repeal 50-a, the state law that allows law enforcement to hide misconduct in their ranks, but that is only step one in our fight to reform policing in New York. NYC Department of Health and Mental Hygiene
May 28 at 10:11 PM ·

COVID-19 is affecting all New Yorkers in one way or another, from
struggling with feelings of uncertainty to fear of the virus itself. Many people are also dealing with loss and grief. Some might experience higher levels of stress, depression or anxiety that can cause trouble sleeping.

Try these tips for better sleep:
😴Establish a sleep routine.
😴Avoid lying down or napping during daytime hours.
😴Lower the amount of caffeine you drink (such as coffee, tea, soda and energy drinks), and avoid drinking caffeine after early afternoon.
😴Increase your physical activity by moving more and sitting less.

Learn more: https://on.nyc.gov/3g8a46m

post_text:
We Speak NYC (WSNYC) is an English language learning program that provides civic-focused instruction through videos centered on topics relevant to immigrant New Yorkers.
Topics include workers’ rights, healthcare, workforce development.
Due to COVID-19, WSNYC is now holding 9 online classes that will give learners opportunity to practice English, safely meet people, learn about City resources, and join an online community.
Classes are led by trained facilitators and encourage learner participation - they offer a safe space to practice and make mistakes.
Classes are intended for intermediate English language learners.
Visit nyc.gov/learnenglish to find online class schedule and drop into a class.

#GUGAlwaysLearning David Brand (editor of the Queens Daily Eagle -- largest publication for all things Queens!) gave a call for artists to submit fun sports-themed coloring pages for Queens kids and families to do while "stuck at home" during quarantine. All of the coloring pages feature the NY Cosmos, the only independent and authentic club in NYC, arguably the most famous club in North America thanks to its legendary players from the 70s, and undeniably the most cosmopolitan! He wants to see your amazing work too! Print out the images from the article here (https://queenseagle.com/all/color-these-pages-cosmos-lauri-scherer-art-at-home) and then submit them to david@queenspublicmedia.com!

Some of our students have already started this fun process, so check out their work below! New York Cosmos 5 Points NYC Queens Daily Eagle The Glitter Goddess Collective + Haus of Glitter Dance Company#GUGAlwaysLearning

post_text:
#GUGIndoorRecess Want to make your own track and field events? Try out this activity and see who can improve their jumping each round!

Make 5–10 separate lines of tape, each about a foot apart, on your floor or carpet. Label the first one the “start” line and then give your kids simple instructions:

Long Jump: See how many lines they can jump over. Have them try and beat their best score each time. Experiment with arm swinging vs. arms behind their backs.
Run ‘n’ Jump: Now let them take a running start and see if they can jump even further!
Long Jump Backwards: Increase the difficulty by performing the tasks jumping backwards.
Hop: How far can they jump on one leg?
Reach ‘n’ Stretch: How far can their leg reach with one foot on the “start” line?
text:

Run ‘n’ Jump: Now let them take a running start and see if they can jump even further!

Senator Leroy Comrie

My office is partnering with Southeast Queens United Professionals Front, our Veterans Advisory Committee, the NYPD, small businesses like Maxine's on the Blvd. and others to provide free Grab & Go meals tomorrow, Thursday, April 23rd to our healthcare workers and seniors in the community. post_text: #GUGIndoorRecess Need a fun new activity? Try the Physical Education challenge the GUG I 3rd-5th graders had to do this week. Simply find a deck of cards and turn them over one at a time. If it's a black card, do as many sit-ups as the number on the card. If it's a red card, do as many squats as the number on the card. Check out one of our fourth graders showing you how it's done!

post_text: FREE Meals for ALL New Yorkers!
shared_text:
New York City Department of Education
April 2 at 9:16 PM ·

NEWS: starting tomorrow, Friday, April 3, 2020 three free meals will be available daily for ALL New Yorkers in more than 400 Meal Hubs across the 5 boroughs!

🔹 Meal Hubs sites operate from 7:30AM-11:30AM for children and families and 11:30AM-1:30PM for adults
🔹 Vegetarian and halal options available at all sites
🔹 All adults and children can pick up three meals at one time
🔹 No one will be turned away
🔹 There is no registration or identification required

To find a location near you visit schools.nyc.gov/freemeals.
